Security Operations Fundamentals > [T2]: Understanding Cloud Computing and CASB

Cloud Access Security Brokers (CASB)

Cloud computing has seen phenomenal growth in recent years. This computing paradigm is based on resource pooling, where cloud providers serve multiple clients with provisional and scalable services. It's a cost-efficient option since customers pay only for what they use. In addition, customers do not have to worry about maintaining these resources.

Almost all enterprises use the cloud in one way or another, and defenders must understand how security works in the cloud to face the evolving dependency on cloud services. We can divide cloud computing models into the following three models:

  • Software as a Service (SaaS): The client is given access to end-user applications hosted in the cloud. A SaaS example is social media platforms (e.g., Facebook, Twitter, etc.).
  • Platform as a Service (PaaS): The client is given access to a runtime environment and processing platforms. Google App Engines are an example of PaaS services. 
  • Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS): The client is given access to a virtualized infrastructure, including servers, storage, and networks. Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2) is an example of an IaaS service.


Figure - zoom in

But what about the security part? A cloud access security broker CASB is software deployed on-premises or in the cloud that acts as an intermediary between users and cloud services/applications. You can think of it as a proxy for your cloud services. The CASB's role is to monitor all activities, enforce security policies, and comply with regulations. This way, organizations will have more control beyond their perimeter.
 

Figure - zoom in

Many providers offer CASB services, such as Microsoft Defender for cloud apps and McAfee CASB MVISION.
